28–Deceased","1430–1498":"1430–1498","1442–Female":"1442–Deceased","1456–Male":"1456–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1445–1512":"1445–1512","1467–Female":"1467–Deceased","–1463":"–1463","–1456":"–1456","1440":"1440","1490":"1490","8 October 1463":"8 October 1463","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1456":"1456","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1442":"1442","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1505":"1505","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Rufford Manor, Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hesketh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): habitational name from Hesketh (Lancashire), Hesketh Grange in Felixkirk (North Yorkshire), or Hesket in the Forest (Cumberland). The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>hestr</i> ‘horse, stallion’ + <i>skeith</i> ‘course, track, race course’. The ancient Scandinavians were fond of horse-racing and horse-fighting, and introduced both pastimes to England."],"variants":[{"name":"Heskett","meanings":["English (Cumberland and Lancashire): variant of   Hesketh  ."]}]},{"name":"Edmund","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protector’. It was borne by several early royal and saintly figures, including a 9th-century king of East Anglia killed by invading Danes, allegedly for his adherence to Christianity. In the 16th and 17th centuries, there was a good deal of interchange between <i>Edmund</i> and <i>Edward</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":10,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Edmund Hesketh ,of Rufford was born in 1445, in Rufford, Lancashire, England as the son of Sir Thomas Hesketh and Margaret Massey. He had at least 1 daughter with Lady Ann Ashton. He died in 1505, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1445–1505":"1445–1505","1427–1490":"1427–1490","1428–Male":"1428–Surnud","1430–1498":"1430–1498","1442–Female":"1442–Surnud","1456–Male":"1456–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1445–1512":"1445–1512","1467–Female":"1467–Surnud","–1463":"–1463","–1456":"–1456","1440":"1440","1490":"1490","8 October 1463":"8. oktoober 1463","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1456":"1456","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1442":"1442","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1505":"1505","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Rufford Manor, Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","Rufford, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Rufford, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1445–1505":"1445–1505","1427–1490":"1427–1490","1428–Male":"1428–Kuollut","1430–1498":"1430–1498","1442–Female":"1442–Kuollut","1456–Male":"1456–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1445–1512":"1445–1512","1467–Female":"1467–Kuollut","–1463":"–1463","–1456":"–1456","1440":"1440","1490":"1490","8 October 1463":"8. lokakuuta 1463","1512":"1512","1445":"1445","1456":"1456","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1442":"1442","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1505":"1505","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Rufford Manor, Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancas